## 5. Common patterns and anti-patterns

### 5.1 Loops and conditionals (`for_each`, `count`)

Use **`for_each`** when iterating over a map or set of strings — it produces
stable, addressable state keys. Use **`count`** only for simple numeric
iteration or single-resource conditional creation (`count = var.enabled ? 1 : 0`).

BAD — `count` over a map:

```terraform
resource "aws_instance" "app_servers" {
  count = length(var.instance_configs) # map → index-keyed state, fragile
  tags = {
    Name = var.instance_configs[count.index].name
  }
}
```

GOOD — `for_each` over a map:

```terraform
resource "aws_instance" "app_servers" {
  for_each = var.instance_configs # map(object({...}))
  tags = {
    Name = each.value.name
  }
}
```

### 5.2 Dynamic blocks

Use `dynamic` blocks to build repeatable nested blocks from a complex variable.
Keep the inner `content` minimal and readable.

```terraform
resource "aws_security_group" "web" {
  # ...
  dynamic "ingress" {
    for_each = var.ingress_rules
    content {
      from_port   = ingress.value.from_port
      to_port     = ingress.value.to_port
      protocol    = ingress.value.protocol
      cidr_blocks = ingress.value.cidr_blocks
    }
  }
}
```

### 5.3 Tagging resources

**Always** tag resources with `Project`, `Description`, `Version`,
`ReleaseDate`, `ManagedBy`. Centralize via `default_tags` in the `provider`
block, and **derive every tag value from `local.solution`** (§1.4) — never
hardcode the account, region, project, or version in `providers.tf`.

```terraform
# infra/aws_tf/providers.tf
provider "aws" {
  region              = local.solution.region
  profile             = "kt-acc"
  allowed_account_ids = [local.solution.account_id]

  default_tags {
    tags = {
      Project     = local.solution.name
      Description = local.solution.description
      Version     = local.solution.version
      ReleaseDate = local.solution.date
      ManagedBy   = "Terraform"
    }
  }
}
```

Child modules inherit `default_tags` from the root provider and **must not**
declare their own `provider "aws"` block.

